<div id="section_1" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div id="sub_section_1" class="section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				As perhaps you've guessed from the class's name, we're going to spend this semester trying to dig into the narrative form of filmmaking and examine in depth different techniques that filmmakers have employed in order to tell stories with images. 	
			</p>
			<p>
				If you've taken Film 114 and Film 210, you've taken the department's two foundational classes designed to provide you with an understanding both of film's cultural history as well as of fundamental filmmaking techniques.
			</p> 
			<p>
				In this class, we'll be spending less time thinking about the technical aspects of filmmaking, though those will still arise from time to time, and spend more time analyzing films to understand the strategy behind the director's structural decisions. We're going to think of a film's structure as a specific recipe designed to create a specific range and progression of emotions. Which ingredients a director chooses to include, and the order in which they're included, are extremely important in defining what that emotional progression ultimately turns out to be. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Here's an example: you've seen countless movies in which the main character, a detective perhaps, or an outlaw of some kind, is ready to retire, but instead decides to perform one last job (or perhaps is being pulled out of retirement to perform one last job). <em>Drive</em>, <em>Unforgiven</em>, <em>Falling Down</em>, <em>Inception</em>, <em>Seven</em>, <em>Grosse Pointe Blank</em>, <em>Blade Runner</em>, and countless other movies employ this now-cliched strategy. Of course the job goes wrong in some way. If the film were just a story of the job, and the job was just one in a long line of identical previous jobs and just one of many more to come, it would simply be a story of a job gone awry. But the director makes a strategic choice to precede the job-gone-wrong with the context of impending retirement. The carrot of "happily ever after" is dangled in front of us–the picture of possible happiness. It's the fact of this carrot that makes the job-gone-wrong that much more emotional. The contrast of potential happiness presented then snatched away enhances the emotional punch of the story. It's such an effective strategy that it's been used dozens of times, to the point that it's more or less lost it's power. While watching <em>Inception</em>, I laughed out loud when Leonardo Dicaprio tells Michael Caine that he just has to do this <em>one last job</em> and he'll be home free. I'm pretty sure laughter was not the emotional reaction Christopher Nolan was aiming for in that scene.
			</p> 

			<p>
				Throughout the semester we'll be fleshing out an idea of what constitutes "traditional" narrative structure. We'll also be attempting to flesh out some ideas about what variations on traditional form are possible and why someone might want to deviate from more accepted patterns. In other words, what unusual or unexpected effects on the viewer can be achieved by avoiding those traditional patterns? 
			</p>
		</div>	
