				<div id="comment_response_section_1" class="first_paragraph">
					<p>
						While it's true that a viewer typically gets satisfaction out of fulfilled expectations and dissatisfaction from thwarted expectations, there are a number of compelling reasons why a filmmaker might be willing to risk causing a bit of viewer frustration. 
					</p>
					<p>
						One simple reason is that if filmmakers only fulfill expectations, then the film viewing experience quickly becomes predictable and dull. As soon as an expectation is raised the viewer already knows exactly what will happen. 
					</p>
					<p>
						Another reason is that thwarting expectations can result in a situation where viewers are forced to reevaluate their assumptions and perhaps come to see the situation in an entirely different light. This process of reevaluation results in a  fairly complicated experience for the viewer and as a result is quite popular with a lot of filmmakers. It's going to figure somewhat heavily in a number of the films we watch this semester. 
					</p>	
				</div>
				
