				<h2>A significant part of the moviemaking process has become the task of manipulating and controlling viewer expectation.</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
			
	</div>
</div>
<div id="section_4">
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div id="section_4_overlay">
			<div id="sub_section_4" class="section">
				<h3>CONVENTIONS AS STRUCTURAL PATTERNS</h3>
				<p>
					Let's talk about a few examples of larger patterns that have recurred throughout film history and have become patterns for providing an overall structure to a film's progression. These patterns are a little broader than the concept of genre. 	
				</p>
				<p id="journey">
					<h3>The Journey</h3>
					<p>
						In this type of film, time is measured out through space. The journey is typically divided up into a series of destinations that incrementally progress through the narrative. As the characters reach one destination, a new one replaces it to provide the next short-term goal in the viewer's mind. The string of mini-journeys functions as a sort of scaffold on which to hang the rest of the film, the character development and emotional progression.
					</p>
				</p>
				<p id="detective">
					<h3>Detective Story</h3>
					<p>
						Here instead of using distance, time is measured out through discoveries. Each small discovery moves the viewer and characters one step closer to the long-term goal and is quickly replaced with a new short-term goal that will lead to the next discovery. 
					</p>
				</p>
				<p id="musical">
					<h3>Musical</h3>
					<p>
						This pattern is a little old-fashioned but has seen a little bit of recurrence of late (particularly in India). In the musical, time is measured out through songs in much the same way it's measured out through destinations and discoveries in the above patterns. Each song serves as a break from the overall flow of the narrative allowing us to reset our expectations about what’s coming next.
					</p>
				</p>
				<p>
					These are just a few of many patterns that have evolved over time. We'll encounter more as we move through the semester. The point is that patterns evolve because they are useful to filmmakers who use them as tools to shape and manipulate viewer expectations throughout the course of a film. 
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
