<div id="section_6b">
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="section sub_section_6b">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
					Let's take a trip back through the film and think about all the different sets of expectations we have as we watch.
				</p>
				<p>
					When we approach the film from the beginning, most likely the primary question in our mind (perhaps subconsciously) is “What is this film about?”, followed closely by “Who are the main characters?” and “What is the main conflict of the film?”
				</p>
				<p>
					The film starts with a few false beginnings that serve to postpone the answer to those questions. We see the fake educational film which gives us a sense of the history of the Alaskan area and helps to set up the backdrop of the conflict between tourism and the fishing industry that provides the social context for the film. This segues into the scene at the closing cannery, depicting the economically downtrodden position of the local population. We might expect that some of the characters we see here will be main characters, but that turns out not to be the case. Finally, we get to the wedding and gradually weave our way through a whole range of different characters. Again, we might think that the characters who get the most screen time––those conversing about the logging industry and tourism––might prove to be the main characters, but again, they are only small bit players. 
				</p>
				<p>
					It takes about seven minutes into the film for us to finally settle in on Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio’s character, the singer, and perhaps get an inkling that she’ll prove to be one of the main characters of the film, but it isn’t until about twelve minutes in that the two main characters finally meet and set off what essentially amounts to the film’s cause-and-effect chain. All the preceding interactions have mostly served to set up the cultural backdrop in which the story will take place. 
				</p>	
					
				<p>
					Even through the introduction to the film, we see John Sayles playing a bit with our expectations in subtle ways. Once we see that Sayles is developing the relationship between Joe and Donna, our expectation most likely has been established that we’ll witness something of a conventional love story. The main question in our minds becomes “Will these two characters end up together?”
				</p>
				<p>
					This remains our primary question up until a critical juncture of the film where everything shifts. When John Sayles introduces the character of the step-brother, there are hints that he’ll figure into some kind of plot complication, but the real shift in our expectations about the film occurs right around the halfway point when we see the gun. 
				</p>	
				<p>
					Here is a significant strategic choice on Sayles' part. As soon as we see it, the gun creates a whole range of expectations that deviate significantly from the expectations we've had up until this point. The film pivots around the weapon, changing course. Now the film is about something else altogether. The story about the developing relationship, instead of being the main focus of the film, becomes the backdrop to some more conventional story about drug smuggling and violence. The questions we had been asking about whether these two characters will overcome their past problems and end up together recede to the back of our minds and the most pressing question becomes "What's going to happen with the gun?"
				</p>	
				<p>
					Why does this shot of the gun cause such a seismic change in our experience of the film and our expectations? It's because of our shared history of movie-watching. It's because of patterns and convention. We've been trained to expect that when a gun appears, it will go off at some point (this dramatic principle even has a name–Chekhov's Gun–after the Russian dramatist Anton Chekhov who famously stated that if a gun is shown in the first act of a play, it had better go off by the third, otherwise there's no reason to show it).
				</p>
				<p>
					In my mind, it’s worth digging in-depth into the question of why Sayles chooses this particular strategy, so we’ll spend time addressing that in this week’s discussion.
				</p>
		</div>
